> I was planning on learning with a $1k budget that i planned to lose so i could get the basics down. Any resources i might want to start with? Selling a digital product
@businesshippie Start with a few books. I'd glance over 


Scientific Advertising - Hopkins, Claude
Breakthrough Advertising Book by Eugene M. Schwartz


For facebook, read https://www.facebook.com/business/learn
Google https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-google-adwords-training-course/ (Its like 15 EUR/USD, the only course I've ever bought because a friend, who owns a fairly successful agency which ONLY does Google ads recommended it to me. Goes over fundamentals and then even more advanced stuff/)

Start with very very low budgets (50 per day) to get a feel for it. Don't make things more complicated than they need to be - if you don't spend much money your account structures should be super simple with just one campaign, so it has a chance in optimization. 

Don't fight the algos, but work with them. Broad targeting options when possible. Have to spend money for data in order to optimize. At first, you're generally only spending money to buy data.

Go over the data you get often and optimize using your campaigns using it.

messages.content: For B2B stuff, it's important to advertise it to people, not to companies. People are the ones making the buying decisions, so you don't have to include jargon heavy corp speech in B2B copy. It just performs better when you approach it (in a niche and brand appropriate, of course) tone.

Generally, if you are able to dish out a budget of at least 10k per month, it is not worth it to mediabuy yourself. Getting a good agency will pay its own cost in gold, unless you know what you're doing. Alternative is to hire an inhouse mediabuyer, if possible.

Lemme drop a laundry list of all the things I've done real quick
Most of it isn't paid stuff considering this is a side gig for me
So having money obviously changes the equation a TON

- Paying to sponsor Content Creators on YouTube ($)
- Cross promoting with other people's newsletters

So we have a bunch of sources that kind of keep us on the pulse of what our readers want - in my case I write about the gaming industry
So we're constantly trying to keep a pulse on the "it thing" or idea that our readers care about - whether thats a game, creator, or whatever
Once we figure it out we try to budget on it someway or another, and then use those channels we know about (mainly twitter + reddit) to put it out there for anyone who signs up
So one time we did a Steam Gift card, and anyone who signed up was eligible to win. Then when we selected a winner we shouted them out in the next issue and made the winning part super public
I'm sure the same idea would work on Insta for sure

Going Viral is like obviously a total crap shoot - so I try to distill it down to two concepts: Likelihood to break out (is the distribution right for your content to catch fire) + quality of viral content (how likely is the thing you're making gonna go viral)

For us - we try to build a solid brand presence on all those channels like Reddit and know exactly where the readers are at + whats going on, so that when the time is right are perfectly positioned to post something that will catch fire

On the quality of the content, a lot of that is listening to readers and tracking how our stuff is doing to see what people like. There is definitely content that is more likely go to viral than others, so optimizing your stuff based on what your readers like is a great way to increase your odds, does that make sense?

messages.content: @WinterCharm  - first off, dope kickstarter and cool product. I've spent a bunch of time in Charelston so fun to see some cool ideas coming out of the city
to me, it seems like the main value prop of what you're building is more technical than your average consumer understands - so you need to go to where the people who see the value live
I think from an organic POV there are a couple ways to do this (obviously none of this is substantiated by user research, which I would recommend doing)

1. Reach out to a handful of influencers in the PC Space and promise them a PC if they promote the kickstarter - obviously want to be sparse here, but could get you over the line 
2. have a friend or backer share the project in places where your consumers live (like r/pcmasterrace for example)
3. Do a giveaway in a free-gaming or freebies subreddit. Ideally you want to be SUPER targeted with where you run this because the ROI can be low if its with a community of people who dont value what youre building

From a Paid POV:
1.  It might actually make sense to run Google Display Ads on PCGamer and other hardware sites that you'll be able to convert from. The idea of someone converting from a paid add to a $300+ seems tough though, and you'll probably burn budget fast, so Im meh on this
2.  Buy something for the giveaway that isn't a PC, maybe something adjacent like a some core software or hardware your users would love
3. Add more minor tiers to your kickstarter! Its $300+ or nothing! Can you add a paid waitlist, merch, hardware components, copys of diagrams? Anything to supplment funding!

messages.content: I feel like "legacy" brands like Petco can get away with this because their logo was never really the centerpiece of their brand identity, and most people know them by their name anyways. I do think it showcases a really interesting evolution in logo design though that was really kicked off by the introduction of mobile apps ~12 years ago. Brands started having to focus on their logo being able to fit into a tiny square box, and still be memorable without being accompanied by the actual brand name. We can see the impact of this shift by looking at some of the massive companies that were born and raised in the mobile-first era, like AirBnb and DoorDash, whose logos are just as identifiable on their own as they are when accompanied by the actual name of the co
^ That was probably not what you were looking for, but your post just made me think of how design priorities have shifted so much and I wanted to say something 😁

Haha not at all, all great points! Yes if you don’t have a distinctive icon/visual vocabulary - it’s damaging to the brand. Like the full length of the Instagram logo in cursive is forgettable. The brown camera that was replaced by the ombré orange pink to purple is now the distinct image that pops up into our head or the white icon outline logo of rounded square with circle within. Although for petco’s case the animals were what I identified with the brand and ignored the letters at least growing up, so it’s a nostalgic loss but whom really has stake in a logo than the ones that remember going to the store and seeing the neon lights. 

I honestly think a lot of this “minimalism” comes from the explosion of co-branding in the past few years. Trying to get the old petco logo next to chewy’s logo, looks messy and non-cohesive. With marketing materials in blog posts, event promotion, announcements, partnerships, and even swag, I think the cohesive unit of two logos put together can even make or break the partnership, but maybe I’m just a picky branding person. Even when I saw the SF acquisition of Slack and how they combined their brand identities, it kind of made me want to throw up with the very child-like color over usage? Hot take: can visual elements be classist by having tiered versions of branding and only branding with similar logos?? Or is it just that big tech goes to all the same creative agencies ... 🤣🤣🤣
I.e. this , also, when will we stop the “+” as a partnership symbol idk

That's a really interesting take on it, and I totally agree it seems like tech branding has started pulling from a more narrow color palette over the last decade or so, or maybe it's always been narrow and they've just made another shift, this time to the ultra-colorful style you mention. Not being a designer myself though, I wonder if it's a result of some shift in popular design theory over the last decade or something. Like, what is it about the palette that designers like so much, or think will be attractive/memorable to customers?

Yeah logo architecture is a headache but also valid. I do think graphic design for logo architecture is not something everyone in a company should participate in creating a brand identity. For example within a company there can be so many programs to engage in but they should still maintain a lower brand identity than the main brand. Facebook does this poorly but probably because I can only imagine how disorganized it is on the inside. For example: Facebook for kids, elevate, groups, messenger even, it’s not cohesive and rings very google drive pre rebrand to me. They all operate as separate functions and don’t try and bring it back to the main function of connecting friends / newsfeed.

The other trend I’ve seen is icon next to the word version of the logo, but never quite separated - the pic is just a few newer apps released. But if you check the app download, it’s just the icon for the obviously lack of space/ size to include full logo. I find this to be uncreative and more utility than design genius, but would want to see how logo design could be more innovative in the future to be more memorable.

A good rule of thumb with any medium in marketing is to ALWAYS stand out from your competition - here are 3 great ways that will help those of you who sell physical products online :

1. Order a bunch of folded cards (think birthday card) and either do it yourself or hire someone to write a hand written message thanking them for their purchase:
It's a GREAT way to make an impact and be memorable by appealing to emotion is to pick a charity that you will donate 10% of your profits to  (you will be paying this 10% to the government in the form of taxes anyway, might as well make it a write off and know where your would be tax money will go to support) and mention this to the customer like :
“We sincerely thank you for your order - and you might not know this but 10% of every order purchased from *Insert Store/Brand Name* goes to benefit *Insert Charity*. If you have any issues with your order please do not hesitate to contact us at *insert email or phone number - phone preferred - use Google Voice  if you don’t have a personal line*” Sincerely,
- Your Name

2. Order a bunch of $5 gift cards to Starbucks or comparable common physical location (coffee is good from a psychological standpoint because it’s an “upper”) - this sounds silly but if you got an unexpected gift card to a place you love - you will associate the brand who gave you that unexpected gift, with the positive feelings for the brand the gift card is for, while also making people think of you when they use it.
It's a GREAT way to make sure they DO think of you when they use it - is to order two stickers with one being a bit bigger than the other - one that has your logo on it with a big bold “Thank You For Shopping With Us” - and the other that has a code and general copy to get 10% off their next order with  big bold red font that says  “KEEP ME”  at the top. MAKE SURE to then place the bottom sticker over the top of the magnetic strip of the gift card and then and then the other sticker ontop of it of the first one covering the copy - intentionally fold one corner revealing a bit of the text. Why? BECAUSE when they go to use it, it can’t be swiped, and it would cause a  “pattern interrupt”  and cause everything to get held up at the cash register and for the barista to likely say something, and then they’ll either hand back the card for the person to peel off the sticker or the barista will peel off the sticker..

If the barista peels it - they’ll see the giant “KEEP ME” and likely hand it back to the owner after purchase or tell the owner of the card about the discount prior to peeling off the bottom sticker to access the magnetic strip. Basically turning a starbucks employee into your “unintentional” sales person 🙂 and remind the customer of your brand and associating it with a positive memory of another discount plus the high of caffeine from the drink they likely ordered with the $5 gift card - not to mention around 15% of people who order from Starbucks go there to use the wifi so guess who’s going to be hear about your shop and then sit down infront of a computer with your 10% gift card? 3. Include a $2 scratcher ticket with a fortune cookie 
- you might think this is crazy but crazy is good because it’s another  “pattern interrupt”  because your customers are expecting just another package 
- this small addition makes it no longer “just another package” 
- it turns it into a chance for winning, which naturally evokes emotion which is then tied to receiving a package from your brand. 
Most $2 scratcher tickets have a 20% - 33% chance of the person winning something - even if it’s just their money back. The fortune cookie is a secondary addition - because most people like fortune cookies (positive association with your brand), the fortune will pique their already increased interest from receiving this scratcher ticket, and the “lucky numbers” on the back could play off the type of scratcher you send. Having a small card with a note that says : “Thank you for your purchase! Here is a little something from us to you! Good luck and let us know if you win by tagging us on either Facebook or instagram with #*insertbrand*!” with an arrow to where fortune cookie taped to the card (likely on the back). It’s a disruptive gesture with three opportunities for positive association - one through the card itself - the second through sensory of eating the cookie - and finally through the endorphins released from the prospect of potentially winning, meanwhile likely getting you a significant amount of shares on social media about your unique approach to customer service. It’s a WIN, WIN, WIN!
